#Text=Paynesville ( Victoria )
#Text=Paynesville is a resort for boating in East Gippsland .
#Text=Understand
#Text=It has a man made canal system for boating as well as a natural harbour area , central to the hundreds of kilometres of lakes and rivers that form part of the Gippsland Lakes system .
#Text=Get in
#Text=Paynesville is around 15 minutes drive from Bairnsdale .
#Text=A small bus runs several times daily between the towns .
#Text=The road between Paynesville and Bairndale has a consistently wide hard shoulder , and it is a nearly dead flat 14km ride from Bairnsdale alongside the Mitchell River .
#Text=There is even a short diversion along a cycle path by the side of the river - although travelling this way involves a climb at the end of the path .
#Text=Trains service Bairnsdale from Melbourne three times daily , and carry bikes .
#Text=You can also travel to Paynesville by boat .
#Text=You can moor at the jetty in front of the town centre for 4 hours free of charge - for longer stays there are plenty of marina and mooring options .
#Text=Get around
#Text=It pays to pick up a local map .
#Text=Some of the online maps services have errors , and do n't show the canals or newer roads .
#Text=A bicycle is perfectly suited to Paynesville .
#Text=The area is flat , the roads are quiet , and the Raymond Island ferry carries bicycles free of charge .
#Text=The town centre is easy to walk around .
#Text=Parking is available everywhere .
#Text=To see many of the areas surrounding the lakes a boat is required .
#Text=There are several options for dingy , cruiser , or kayak hire in town .
#Text=Bulls Cruisers .
#Text=See
#Text=Raymond Island .
#Text=The island ferry is just a short trip from the town centre .
#Text=$ 8 return for cars , or free for bicycles and pedestrians .
#Text=There is a waterfront walk/cycle , and paths and roads which meander through the trees .
#Text=There is a large population of Koala 's on the island , and this would have to be one of the easiest places in Australia to spot Koalas .
#Text=There is also a large variety of sea birds and wallabies .
#Text=Silt Jetties .
#Text=The silt jetties near Eagle Point are the second longest in the world , after those on the Mississippi .
#Text=They are caused by deposits of silt made by the Mitchell river as it flooded , and results in a thin strip of land between 50m and 10m wide stretching right out into the lake .
#Text=You can drive along them , just take the Eagle Point Road , and keep on going .
#Text=There is a lookout at The Bluff , but the best experience is to drive or cycle right out along them .
#Text=Do
#Text=Swimming .
#Text=The foreshore area is reserved for swimmers .
#Text=The water is calm , the beach is sandy , and it is a good place to cool off .
#Text=It is n't really the destination for those looking for a spectacular beach or for a beach scene .
#Text=There are a few small jellyfish around , but they probably wo n't bother you .
#Text=Boating .
#Text=This is what Paynesville is all about .
#Text=If you have your own boat , you will be right at home here .
#Text=Otherwise you can hire a cruiser for around $ 200 a day , or a kayak for around $ 50 .
#Text=You can cross the lake directly to 90-mile beach - which is an ocean beach around 45 minutes away by boat at 8 knots .
#Text=You can circle Raymond Island , or you can spend several days or a week exploring the lake and river system .
#Text=Cycling .
#Text=There is no challenging mountain biking here - Paynesville and Raymond Island are almost completely flat .
#Text=There are numerous bush tracks and a waterfront track on Raymond Island .
#Text=You can spot koalas and other wildlife as you cycle around .
#Text=For the best koala viewing , just cross on the ferry and continue up Seventh Avenue .
#Text=You can cycle all the way to the other side of the island , with numerous diversions along the way .
#Text=Buy
#Text=Supplies are easily available - supermarkets stock a wide variety of goods , and are open until 8pm daily .
#Text=Paynesville Dairy , is open Monday , Wednesday , Friday from 11am until 5pm , stocking local dairy products , including milk and cheese .
#Text=Eat
#Text=There are four cafe/restaurant style places to choose from along the main strip opposite the foreshore .
#Text=The coffee market is competitive - with the boaties demanding a good coffee on deck in the morning .
#Text=Fishermans Wharf Cafe , ☏ +61351560366 .
#Text=Opens 8am for coffee and breakfast , and remains open for lunch and dinner .
#Text=The only one of the cafes on the waterfront side of the Esplanade .
#Text=Great views over the water for brunch , and has an alfresco eating area .
#Text=Cappuccino made like a big hot and frothy coffee and chocolate milkshake .
#Text=The pub serves meals for lunch and dinner every day , and there are a couple of clubs serving similar style pub fare .
#Text=Paynesville Motor Cruiser Club ( On Barrabogie Island , past Bulls Cruisers ) .
#Text=Large open room right on the water .
#Text=Casual Mains around $20-$ 25 .
#Text=There is a pizza place to eat in or take away , two bakeries selling a large variety of pies and cakes , and a fish and chip shop .
#Text=Drink
#Text=After a day on the lakes or seeing the sights , you will have no problem getting a quiet beer with a view .
#Text=Do n't expect too much in the way of nightlife .
#Text=The Old Pub ( On the Esplanade in the centre of town , right opposite the ferry ) .
#Text=Fairly standard Victorian country pub , on the esplanade , but it is n't constructed to maximise the view or the location .
#Text=Has accommodation too
#Text=Sleep
#Text=Captains Cove .
#Text=Villas along an inlet off the canal that forms Barrabogie Island .
#Text=Each villa has its own pier and boat parking space on the water right in front of it .
#Text=Connect
#Text=There is mobile reception in town , but the signal is weak and limited in many parts away from the town centre .
#Text=Telstra has 3G mobile Internet , but Optus and Vodafone struggle with even GPRS .
